      <span class="search-hit">Abstract</span>:
      <span class="abstract-short has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="2103.11977v1-abstract-short" style="display: inline;">
        We investigate the group gradings on the <span class="search-hit mathjax">algebra</span> of upper triangular matrices over an arbitrary field, viewed as a Lie <span class="search-hit mathjax">algebra</span>. These results were obtained a few years early by the same authors. We provide streamlined proofs, and present a complete classification of isomorphism classes of the gradings. We also provide&hellip;
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('2103.11977v1-abstract-full').style.display = 'inline'; document.getElementById('2103.11977v1-abstract-short').style.display = 'none';">&#9661; More</a>
      </span>
      <span class="abstract-full has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="2103.11977v1-abstract-full" style="display: none;">
        We investigate the group gradings on the <span class="search-hit mathjax">algebra</span> of upper triangular matrices over an arbitrary field, viewed as a Lie <span class="search-hit mathjax">algebra</span>. These results were obtained a few years early by the same authors. We provide streamlined proofs, and present a complete classification of isomorphism classes of the gradings. We also provide a classification of the practical isomorphism classes of the gradings, which is a better alternative way to consider these gradings up to being essentially the same object. Finally, we investigate in details the case where the characteristic of the base field is $2$, a topic that was neglected in previous works.
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('2103.11977v1-abstract-full').style.display = 'none'; document.getElementById('2103.11977v1-abstract-short').style.display = 'inline';">&#9651; Less</a>
      </span>
    </p>
    

