    <p class="title is-5 mathjax">
      
        A combinatorial realization of Kirillov-Reshetikhin crystals for type E arising from translations
      
    </p>
    <p class="authors">
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Authors:</span>
      
      <a href="/search/?searchtype=author&amp;query=Jang%2C+I">Il-Seung Jang</a>
      
    </p>
    
    <p class="abstract mathjax">
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Abstract</span>:
      <span class="abstract-short has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="2103.11510v2-abstract-short" style="display: inline;">
        The purpose of this paper is to give a combinatorial realization of Kirillov-Reshetikhin (KR simply) crystals $B^{r, s}$ for type $\text{E}_n^{(1)}$ with a minuscule node $r$ and $s \ge 1$. It is obtained from the crystal of the quantum nilpotent subalgebra associated with the translation by the negative of the $r$-th fundamental weight, which can be viewed as the limit of KR crystals $B^{r, s}$ a&hellip;
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('2103.11510v2-abstract-full').style.display = 'inline'; document.getElementById('2103.11510v2-abstract-short').style.display = 'none';">&#9661; More</a>
      </span>
      <span class="abstract-full has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="2103.11510v2-abstract-full" style="display: none;">
        The purpose of this paper is to give a combinatorial realization of Kirillov-Reshetikhin (KR simply) crystals $B^{r, s}$ for type $\text{E}_n^{(1)}$ with a minuscule node $r$ and $s \ge 1$. It is obtained from the crystal of the quantum nilpotent subalgebra associated with the translation by the negative of the $r$-th fundamental weight, which can be viewed as the limit of KR crystals $B^{r, s}$ as $s \rightarrow \infty$. Then the KR crystal $B^{r, s}$ is characterized by a certain statistic given in terms of triple and quadruple paths, while it was known that the statistic for types $\text{A}_n^{(1)}$ and $\text{D}_n^{(1)}$ is given in terms of single and double paths, respectively.
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('2103.11510v2-abstract-full').style.display = 'none'; document.getElementById('2103.11510v2-abstract-short').style.display = 'inline';">&#9651; Less</a>
      </span>
    </p>
    

    <p class="is-size-7"><span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Submitted</span> 28 March, 2021; <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">v1</span> submitted 21 March, 2021;
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">originally announced</span> March 2021.
      
    </p>
    
