    <p class="abstract mathjax">
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Abstract</span>:
      <span class="abstract-short has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="2103.10228v2-abstract-short" style="display: inline;">
        Weaving knots $W(p, n)$ of type $(p, n)$ denote an infinite family of hyperbolic knots which have not been addressed by the knot theorists as yet. Unlike the well-known $(p,n)$ torus knots, we do not have a closed-form expression for HOMFLY-PT and the colored HOMFLY-PT for $W(p,n)$. In this paper, we confine to a hybrid generalization of $W(3,n)$ which we denote as $\hat{W}_3(m,n)$ and obtain a cl&hellip;
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('2103.10228v2-abstract-full').style.display = 'inline'; document.getElementById('2103.10228v2-abstract-short').style.display = 'none';">&#9661; More</a>
      </span>
      <span class="abstract-full has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="2103.10228v2-abstract-full" style="display: none;">
        Weaving knots $W(p, n)$ of type $(p, n)$ denote an infinite family of hyperbolic knots which have not been addressed by the knot theorists as yet. Unlike the well-known $(p,n)$ torus knots, we do not have a closed-form expression for HOMFLY-PT and the colored HOMFLY-PT for $W(p,n)$. In this paper, we confine to a hybrid generalization of $W(3,n)$ which we denote as $\hat{W}_3(m,n)$ and obtain a closed-form expression for HOMFLY-PT using the Reshitikhin and Turaev method involving $\mathcal R$-matrices. Further, we also compute $[r]$-colored HOMFLY-PT for $W(3,n)$. Surprisingly, we observe that trace of the product of two dimensional $\hat{\mathcal{R}}$-matrices can be written in terms of an infinite family of Laurent polynomials $\mathcal{V}_{n,t}[q]$ whose absolute coefficients has an interesting relation to the Fibonacci numbers $\mathcal{F}_{n}$. We also computed reformulated invariants and the BPS integers in the context of topological strings. From our analysis, we propose that certain refined BPS integers for weaving knot $W(3,n)$ can be explicitly derived from the coefficients of Chebyshev polynomials of the first kind.
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('2103.10228v2-abstract-full').style.display = 'none'; document.getElementById('2103.10228v2-abstract-short').style.display = 'inline';">&#9651; Less</a>
      </span>
    </p>
    

    <p class="is-size-7"><span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Submitted</span> 27 March, 2021; <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">v1</span> submitted 18 March, 2021;
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">originally announced</span> March 2021.
      
    </p>
    
    <p class="comments is-size-7">
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Comments:</span>
      <span class="has-text-grey-dark mathjax">32 pages, typos corrected</span>
    </p>
    

    

    
  </li>

  <li class="arxiv-result">
    <div class="is-marginless">
      <p class="list-title is-inline-block"><a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2103.10204">arXiv:2103.10204</a>
        <span>&nbsp;[<a href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2103.10204">pdf</a>, <a href="https://arxiv.org/ps/2103.10204">ps</a>, <a href="https://arxiv.org/format/2103.10204">other</a>]&nbsp;</span>
      </p>
      <div class="tags is-inline-block">
        <span class="tag is-small is-link tooltip is-tooltip-top" data-tooltip="Operator Algebras">math.OA</span>
        
          
            <span class="tag is-small is-grey tooltip is-tooltip-top" data-tooltip="Group Theory">math.GR</span>
          
        </div>
      
    </div>
    
    <p class="title is-5 mathjax">
      
        The C*-<span class="search-hit mathjax">algebra</span> of the variable Mautner group
      
    </p>
    <p class="authors">
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Authors:</span>
      
      <a href="/search/?searchtype=author&amp;query=Regeiba%2C+H">Hedi Regeiba</a>
      
    </p>
    
    <p class="abstract mathjax">
      <span class="search-hit">Abstract</span>:
      <span class="abstract-short has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="2103.10204v1-abstract-short" style="display: inline;">
        &hellip;-<span class="search-hit mathjax">algebra</span> $C^*(\M)$ of $\M$ in terms of an <span class="search-hit mathjax">algebra</span> of operator fields defined over $P\times{\C^2} $.
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('2103.10204v1-abstract-full').style.display = 'inline'; document.getElementById('2103.10204v1-abstract-short').style.display = 'none';">&#9661; More</a>
      </span>
      <span class="abstract-full has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="2103.10204v1-abstract-full" style="display: none;">
        Let $\M=P\times{M}$ be a variable Mautner group. We describe the $C^*$-<span class="search-hit mathjax">algebra</span> $C^*(\M)$ of $\M$ in terms of an <span class="search-hit mathjax">algebra</span> of operator fields defined over $P\times{\C^2} $.
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('2103.10204v1-abstract-full').style.display = 'none'; document.getElementById('2103.10204v1-abstract-short').style.display = 'inline';">&#9651; Less</a>
      </span>
    </p>
    

    <p class="is-size-7"><span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Submitted</span> 18 March, 2021; 
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">originally announced</span> March 2021.
      
    </p>
    

    
      <p class="comments is-size-7">
        

        
          <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">MSC Class:</span>
